e recovery. Using research in biomedical and behavioral science, Scott examines accounts of miracle cures at medieval, early modern, and contemporary shrines. He inquires into the power of relics, apparitions, and the transformative nature of sacred journeying and shines new light on the roles belief, hope, and emotion can play in healing.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHealingxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aMiracles. 0aSpiritual healing. 7aRELIGION / Comparative Religion.2bisacsh  aapparitions.  abehavioral science.  abiomedical.  achaucer.  achristian faith.  achristian miracles.  achristianity.  acompostela.  acontemporary shrines.  adisease.  afaith healing.  afatima.  agod and religion.  ahealing powers.  ahealth issues.  ahuman condition.  alourdes.  amedieval pilgrims.  amedjugorje.  amiracles.  amiraculous cures.  aphenomenon.  apilgrimage.  apower of god.  apower of prayer.  arecovery.  arelics.  areligious pilgrimages.  areligious shrines.  asacred journeys.  asaints.  aspiritual.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052026275140uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052094620040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520946200423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520946200/original  a978-3-11-069042-2  University of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY